## The Private IP Problem and NAT

Now we have been talking a bunch of stuff about our IP addresses or ID cards. But in the whole world there is a really big problem. We have way more objects than we have ID cards. So how do we work around that constraint? We use private IP address ranges within a network.

These ranges are very big. One class of those ID cards reaches a little over 16 million addresses and the fewest is around the tens of thousands. These ranges are private, and in fact your IP address right now is probably also part of a private range.

So how is it that if you use a private ID card you are still able to use the internet? The answer is NAT, or Network Address Translation. It allows you to use your private IP address or ID card and turn it into an ID card that is public and therefore can access the internet. Think of it like the room having a single public-facing mailbox at the building entrance. Everyone inside the room has their own private ID card but when mail needs to go out to the world it all goes through that one mailbox with the building's public address on it. When replies come back the mailbox knows which room object to deliver it to. Nobody outside the building ever sees your private ID card, just the mailbox address.

The basic design standard that defines these private IP address ranges is called RFC 1918. Here is a quick look at the three ranges it defines:

**10.0.0.0/8**
- Range: 10.0.0.0 to 10.255.255.255
- Number of addresses: 16,777,216
- Class: Single Class A
- Subnet mask: 255.0.0.0
- Host ID size: 24 bits, meaning three quarters of the address is assigned to hosts

**172.16.0.0/12**
- Range: 172.16.0.0 to 172.31.255.255
- Number of addresses: roughly 1 million

**192.168.0.0/16**
- Range: 192.168.0.0 to 192.168.255.255
- Number of addresses: roughly 65,000
- This is the one your home network is most likely running right now

