## DHCP

Now you can go on and stick all of the ID cards yourself onto every object in your room and that is okay, but it takes time. And would you really want to be bothered with that unless you have a really good reason? Hell no. That is where a robot butler comes in to do it for you.

This butler is interesting though. He sees an object walk in without an ID card asking if there is a butler or someone around to give it one. The butler comes up and offers one, the object says thanks and agrees to use it, and the butler says acknowledged and marks it as done. The real term for this process is DORA: Discover, Offer, Request, and Acknowledge.

Now remember the butler is leasing the ID card, not giving it permanently. If an object is no longer using the ID card the butler gave it, the butler will take it back and give it to another object that needs it more. That is why for reserved IPs the butler is told by you ahead of time that this specific ID card is going to stay with this specific object no matter what.

For everything else, DHCP gives your object three things when it hands out the welcome package: your IP address which is the seat number, your subnet mask which is the room definition, and your default gateway which is the door out of the room to the rest of the building.

---

## APIPA

But DHCP has a cousin who is very shy and only pops up if her butler cousin cannot come. We call her APIPA, or Automatic Private IP Addressing. This shy maid does most of what her butler cousin can do but because she is so shy the ID cards and welcome package she gives out can only work within the room she is assigned to and only between the objects inside that same room. She also carries a limited rack of ID cards she can hand out, ranging from 169.254.1.0 through 169.254.254.255, with the first and last of the wider range being reserved just like any subnet.

What makes her even more unique is that she is self-sufficient. She does not need a list from you. She just picks a card off her rack on her own and checks if anyone else in the room is already using it before handing it over. No butler, no instructions, she just figures it out herself.

The important thing to remember is that her ID cards cannot get you out of the room. There is no gateway, no door to the rest of the building, no internet. So on the AZ-104, if you ever see a device with a 169.254.x.x address treat it as a red flag. It means the butler never showed up and something went wrong with DHCP.

